vent were analyzed coherently across the LIGO network using a\nsuite of accurate waveform models that describe gravitational waves from a\ncompact binary system in general relativity. GW150914 was produced by a nearly\nequal mass binary black hole of $36^{+5}_{-4} M_\\odot$ and $29^{+4}_{-4}\nM_\\odot$; for each parameter we report the median value and the range of the\n90% credible interval. The dimensionless spin magnitude of the more massive\nblack hole is bound to be $<0.7$ (at 90% probability). The luminosity distance\nto the source is $410^{+160}_{-180}$ Mpc, corresponding to a redshift\n$0.09^{+0.03}_{-0.04}$ assuming standard cosmology. The source location is\nconstrained to an annulus section of $610$ deg$^2$, primarily in the southern\nhemisphere. The binary merges into a black hole of $62^{+4}_{-4} M_\\odot$ and\nspin $0.67^{+0.05}_{-0.07}$. This black hole is significantly more massive than\nany other inferred from electromagnetic observations in the stellar-mass\nregime.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 Feb 2016 19:26:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Jun 2016 11:16:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-06-21"}
